pean Humanities of Early Reports from Catholic Missionaries from China, Tibet and Japan between 1600 and 1700 -- tThe Middle Kingdom in the Low Countries: Sinology in the Seventeenth- Century Netherlands -- tThe Oriental Origins of Orientalism: The Case of Dimitrie Cantemir -- tV. Artworks and Texts -- tThe Role of Emotions in the Development of Artistic Theory and the System of Literary Genres -- tPhilology and the History of Art -- tVI. Literature and Rhetoric -- tBourgeois versus Aristocratic Models of Scholarship: Medieval Studies at the Académie des Inscriptions, 1701-1751 -- tAncients, Moderns and the Gothic in Eighteenth-Century Historiography -- tThe Afterlife of Rhetoric in Hobbes, Vico and Nietzsche -- tVII. Academic Communities -- tThe Documents of Feith: The Centralization of the Archive in Nineteenth- Century Historiography -- tHumboldt in Copenhagen: Discipline Formation in the Humanities at the University of Copenhagen in the Nineteenth Century -- tThe Scholarly Self: Ideals of Intellectual Virtue in Nineteenth-Century Leiden -- tContributors -- tList of Figures -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aWhile it is clear that around 1800 the humanities as a discipline rose to prominence, it is less clear what the exact nature of this shift in academia was. Was it a sudden revolution caused by a momentary but powerful change in the zeitgeist or the turning point of a much longer process? In this volume, the editors have selected a series of essays that look at the origins of the humanities and find that long before 1800 the concept of the humanities was already at the fore. The shift around 1800 was thus mostly institutional, not theoretical. The Making of the Humanities traces this new finding through a broad range of disciplines including literary theory, linguistics, art history, and musicology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made ava